{{ja-kanjitab|おぎ|yomi=kun}}

From {{inh|ja|ojp|sort=おぎ|-}}.  Found in the ''{{w|Man'yōshū}}'', completed some time after 759 CE.<ref name="MYS">{{RQ:Manyoshu|14|3446}}, text [http://jti.lib.virginia.edu/japanese/manyoshu/Man14Yo.html#3446 here]</ref>

Ultimate derivation {{unk|ja|nocap=1|sort=おぎ}}.  One theory suggests that it might be the {{m|ja|連用形|tr=ren'yōkei||continuative or stem form}} of classical verb {{m|ja|招く|tr={{upright|ancient reading}} woku, {{upright|modern rendering}} oku||to invite, to beckon someone closer|pos=also found in some texts with the ancient reading ''wogu''}}, from the way the grass waves in the wind.
